commits.commitMessage:
[R2C] Implement SIM Reachability (EDM) feature

- New lwm2m object to support SIM Reachability
- AVC supports multiple instances of Objects 0 and 1
  (DM credentials/properties)
- AVC to be able to manage sessions with 2 (or more) DM servers
- Receive SIM APDU response from the modem FW and provide it
  to R2C DM server
- Device must provide to the Bootstrap server an indication for
  EDM support

Resolves: LE-14723 LE-14736 LE-14774 LE-14775 LE-15155
Change-Id: I48d3545d3fedcb8c2a85f0a4c6550cd74fc9686c
commits.subject: [R2C] Implement SIM Reachability (EDM) feature

commits.commitMessage:
QTI9X07TX-2871-Legato URC sending modification for new qapi_atfwd_send_urc_resp()

Goals:
URC response will no longer automatic generate colon for us , so we have to add a colon symbol in the URC response.

Solution:
We can't use just one buffer to output the whole response , so I created another buffer to split the response into command name and response message.

commits.commitMessage:
Wait for QMI service ready in AtFwdLinker (RC51)

Description:
On latest RC51 code base, some atAirVantage at commands are not responsive and just return "ERROR". These commands include at least "at+wdss", "at+wdsi", "at+wdsc".

Solution:
Use Sierra implemented ATFWD API in QTI9X05-319 and get notify once ATFWD QMI service is ready

Resolves: QTI9X05-319 LE-14872 ATSWI-65
Change-Id: Ic494a9c2ad6d3f41883e61af529ba5e7ff6fc2f2
commits.subject: Wait for QMI service ready in AtFwdLinker (RC51)

comments.message: this patch resolves: LE-14872 and ATSWI-65, would you add this part in the message?
we can remove this #if/#endif, because this file is only available on ThreadX, so if the code works on both RC76 and RC51, we don't need any #if.
is LE_CONFIG_TARGET_GILL defined for RC51? I get compilation error
So, Can you please elaborate more what should be removed here?
Removing lines 59 and 66 should be fine.

We basically avoid using platform specific macro such as LE_CONFIG_TARGET_RC51 in code, if you can rename atfwd_ready_callback_reg to swi_atfwd_ready_reg_callback, which is consistent with RC76, then we can avoid using #if here.

atfwd_ready_callback_reg is defined in SIERRA_AT and we can't rename it to swi_atfwd_ready_reg_callback.
Perhaps, we should ask other team to use SIERRA_AT package for better consistency.
Is it necessary to rename this variable?
yes, AtCmd is defined in SIERRA_AT's API (at/api/atudefs.h).
Why do we have a different function name in RC51?
because the API has been added to SIERRA_AT package instead of changing QTI codes.

commits.commitMessage:
Wait for QMI service ready in AtFwdLinker

Issue Description:
The AVMS related AT commands return "NOT IMPLEMENTED" after FW bundle FOTA update.
This ticket is cloned by QTI9X07TX-1439

Root Cause:
The AT forward mechanism could be abnormal if invoking qapi_atfwd_reg() when QMI
service is not ready. And the AVMS related AT commands are the earliest commands
invoke qapi_atfwd_reg(). These AT forward commands will be affected easily.

Solution:
Wait for QMI service ready by notified from QTI bridge and then register AT forward
commands.

Resolves: LE-14600
Change-Id: I5488a3a7f866bdce8aba6b7ebfae4725c45409de
Signed-off-by: Chiate.Wang <CWang@sierrawireless.com>
(cherry picked from commit 0b8054d857f9b52282e1d034100c1f998beb1bb0)
commits.subject: Wait for QMI service ready in AtFwdLinker

comments.message: Why this patch is only for RC76? RC51 also need this patch, right?

AtFwdLinkerComponent is only available on ThreadX (RC76 and RC51). Is this code not applicable to both RC76 and RC51? 
Same goes to below code as well.
If this patch is only applicable to a specific threadX module, please write a comment explaining why so.

We found that ThreadX in APSS boots up quickly than MPSS in some situations. The AT forwarding mechanism will be invalid. So we add a mechanism to fix it.
Since RC51 also uses ThreadX, this patch should be also applicable to RC51.
But this mechanism depends on the swi_atfwd_ready_reg_callback() API provided by the QTI bridge. Not sure if this API is also available in RC51 or if the RC51 team is willing to use the same solution. So we use RC76 to define it.
Base on Tom's suggestion, we will use cflags/buildVars in sdef to define it and have a comment.

swi_atfwd_ready_reg_callback() is not yet available on RC51 (ticket: QTI9X05-319). The same issue has been created two tickets, one for RC76 master (LE-14600), and the other for RC51 (LE-14872).So, maybe we can get this patch for RC76 master first after solving all review comments and remove #if LE_CONFIG_TARGET_GILL and #if LE_CONFIG_TARGET_RC51 when solving LE-14872.

We add a comment to explain why first.
If RC51 has the same issue and solution, then the #if LE_CONFIG_TARGET_GILL can be removed directly after solving it in RC51.

commits.commitMessage:
Remove the unnecessary 2 second sleep

Previouly we added this 2 second sleep to allow the modem firmware to
get ready for registering AT commands.

However, this 2 second sleep will cause race condition for apps adding
AT command, and the latest modem firmware doesn't require sleeping at
least 2 seconds before registering AT commands anymore, so we remove
this problematic and unnecessary sleep.

Resolves: LE-14036
Change-Id: I142d692ded3b4927b9c841c37e2fa77b7f006115
commits.subject: Remove the unnecessary 2 second sleep

commits.commitMessage:
KTCPCFG only could save up to 18 sessions

Issue Description:
We could write 32 session records by AT+KTCPCFG write command. But we only get 18 records when we try to read it by AT+KTCPCFG?
This ticket is cloned by QTI9X07TX-1352

Root Cause:
Response buffer size too small

Solution:
Increase at response buffer size from 1024 to 2048 bytes

Change-Id: Ib7857020248f8e69381e6cb273fcbf65ef2f4e1b
Resolves: LE-14316
Signed-off-by: CSU <csu@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: KTCPCFG only could save up to 18 sessions

commits.commitMessage:
Handle illegal AT command syntax 'AT='

When an illegal AT command is received, such as 'AT+KURCCFG=' (no
parameters after the '=' character), the module should output
'+CME ERROR: 3' to indicate the syntax error. However, since we didn't
handle this illegal syntax in atFwdLinker, the module didn't response
correctly in this use case.

Add logic in atFwdLinker so the module can response to this type of
illegal AT command syntax appropriately.

Resolves: LE-14046
Change-Id: Ib596ce616dbdc0a46f90e9cd7942f390a2c38d2d
commits.subject: Handle illegal AT command syntax 'AT='

commits.commitMessage:
Support mutiple AT ports in AtFwdLinker

Previously we only supported USB AT port, because we didn't know how to
identify where AT commands are coming from.

Now we've learned that we can identify the source of an AT command from
the ATFWD callback function, so we removed the hard-coded AT port
constant and added firmware APIs to support multiple AT ports.

Resolves: LE-13956
Change-Id: I5c504b0635a3034fc93a1a4c0c8d5a1e416e03cc
commits.subject: Support mutiple AT ports in AtFwdLinker

comments.message: Is this configurable or fixed? Is it better to define it in KConfig?

This file is ThreadX specific.  I think for now it's OK to assume all ThreadX products will have exactly 5 AT ports.  If a different product breaks the mold, we can refactor to make it configurable later.
I think it's better to make this static const at file scope.

commits.commitMessage:
Enhance final response parsing logic

In LE-13915, we enhanced the response parsing logic so that atFwdLinker
can handle multiple responses in one read operation when we increase the
queue length in pipe. However, that patch only handles static final
responses with fixed string length, and doesn't handle dynamic final
responses, such as '+CME ERROR:', which have variable string length.

In this patch, we enhance the final response parsing logic so it can
handle dynamic final responses, too.

Resolves: LE-14049
Change-Id: I2f7d166c503398a7def5e95fc1f4f94319e1ff76
commits.subject: Enhance final response parsing logic

commits.commitMessage:
Enhance atFwdLinker response parsing logic

Previously atFwdLinker assumes that each pipe read operation will only
receive one response, which can be either intermediate, final, or
unsolicited response.

However, when we increase the queue length, atFwdLinker will receive
multiple responses in one read operation, and its response parsing logic
will fail to detect the final response.

We enhance the response parsing logic, so it can handle multiple
responses in a single read buffer.

Resolves: LE-13915
Change-Id: I9d7575ef4fce241bc62ecf96c28c8db9f7c46827
commits.subject: Enhance atFwdLinker response parsing logic

commits.commitMessage:
Use a registration handler to register AT commands

Previouly we use an array of static strings to register AT commands in
atFwdLinker. It's tedious to maintain the array because we have to
remember updating it when we add a new AT command handler, or the
command handler won't get called.

Now we utilize the AT command registration handler already existed in
atServer, so we no longer need to maintain the array of static strings.
When we call le_atServer_AddCommandHandler to register a new AT command
handler, the system will automatically register the AT command to the
modem firmware.

Resolves: LE-13842
Change-Id: I0b166eeb7f0f261c58863cb1ba0a6f92ed25bfe9
commits.subject: Use a registration handler to register AT commands

commits.commitMessage:
Return ERROR responses for illegal AT commands

When you enter an illegal AT command, such as "AT+KFTPCFG=" without any
parameter, the Qualcomm modem firmware will notify us by sending a mask
value to the AT_FWD callback function.

Previously we ignored this mask and kept processing the illegal AT
command, which makes the system hanging for a period of time. Now we
will return ERROR final reponses immediately when users enter illegal AT
commands.

Resolves: LE-13984
Change-Id: Iacf31386a5b6b35ca4928062946ec1707f0d7261
commits.subject: Return ERROR responses for illegal AT commands

commits.commitMessage:
Enhance atFwdLinker to handle consecutive commas

Users are allowed to skip optional AT command parameters by typing
consecutive commas. However, previously atFwdLinker didn't handle
skipped optional parameters properly.

With the enhancement, atFwdLinker can handle at most 9 consecutive
skipped optional parameters, which should be good enough for all of the
known AT command syntax in Sierra Wireless modules.

Resolves: LE-13914
Change-Id: Ief3db8bb57a10e206aa901a48d8a57a68352cd11
commits.subject: Enhance atFwdLinker to handle consecutive commas

comments.message:
Two things i notice about this code:
- If you change UTILSATFWD_MAX_CONSECUTIVE_COMMA, you will have to modify the reset of the if statement
- It's kind of inefficient as you have to check the preceding 10 values when you iterate through the loop

What I would do differently is have a counter and keep track of the number of consecutive nulls and once it hits UTILSATFWD_MAX_CONSECUTIVE_COMMA, break then. I'd also put this in it's own function as utils_GetAtFwdParamLength()
Agree. Will improve this code snippet.

commits.commitMessage:
Integrate firmware Data Forward API

atFwdLinker now is also responsible for initializing a Data Pipe device
and transferring data between firmware and apps.

We also register a new AT command, +KFTPCNX, for testing the firmware
Switch Mode API and Data Forward API.

Resolves: LE-13682
Change-Id: Ica9a2e0dbf8e73fdeb6367f7dcaa1646d1c5ade6
commits.subject: Integrate firmware Data Forward API

comments.message: Why do these need to be threads? Can't you do everthing here like waiting till it's ready and registering the fd monitors?
This is a requirement of the firmware implementation. The firmware needs us to put the Data Forward callback function and the fdMonitor callback function in different threads.
Where is this coming from? Is this the same a LE_CONFIG_PIPE_BLOCK_SIZE?

The value is based on LE_CONFIG_PIPE_BLOCK_SIZE. However, the meaning of this constant should be independent of the underlying implementation details, so we use a number instead of LE_CONFIG_PIPE_BLOCK_SIZE directly.

commits.commitMessage:
Move the pipe initialization to portService

We accidentally changed the portService architecture in atFwdLinker. In
order to keep the original portService design, we move the
initialization of the pipe between atFwdLinker and atService to
portService.

Resolves: LE-13487
Change-Id: I0952d74b21a729903fbec3b07c60fad6403f5a9a
commits.subject: Move the pipe initialization to portService

Implement sending unsolicited response to the modem using Qualcomm QAPI.

Resolves: LE-13497

comments.message: Characters should be compared to '\0' or 0, not NULL.

If modifying the string in bufPtr is allowed, you could just replace the colon with a '\0' and then the part before the colon is bufPtr an the part after is posColon + 1.  If bufPtr shouldn't be modified then you should make the parameter a const char *.

commits.commitMessage:
[atFwdLinker] Miscellaneous fixes

This patch covers the following in atFwdLinker app:
- Reduce buffer size required to store AT command name.
- Remove global variable AtEvent. Keep it local and use get function
  that gets a pointer to AtEvent.
- Other miscellaneous fixes.

Resolves: LE-13646
Change-Id: I8c30165230db00365b82b43e8b02f4a95e99cef8
commits.subject: [atFwdLinker] Miscellaneous fixes

comments.message: Can we guarantee that atCmdName always exists?
DoCleanup() calls pthread_exit(EXIT_SUCCESS). Why exit with EXIT_SUCCESS when we fail to read?
count will never be 0. It will be either > 0 when successfully read the data, or -1 when there's nothing to be read.
@Tom: read returns 0 if you hit EOF.  For an IPC this will generally occur if the remote end is closed.
Need to call sched_yield() in a busy loop?
Why not leave this in AtEvent_t structure?

Use le_utf8_Copy() or strncpy() instead?  Using snprintf() in this way opens up the possibility of a bug as atCmdName is interpreted as a format string.  

It could even lead to a security hole if an attacker can influence what gets passed into atCmdName at some point.  E.g. an atCmdName "+%n" will result in 1 getting written to some unknown location in memory.
What if count == 0?  I.e. other end of connection is closed.
This doesn't really solve the issue I was discussing.  Thinking about it, I think just stay with the original code (assuming that's copied from existing code in Legato).

Reverted as per our discussion and raised this ticket for refactoring:
https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/LE-13677

Sorry, this is the correct ticket:
https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/LE-13684
Why was this removed?  This seems like a serious change which will mess up error handling logic.

What if you get EAGAIN?  You shouldn't call sendResponse in that case.  In fact EAGAIN should never be returned here, since you are processing a POLLIN so the OS (via Legato) is letting you know this pipe is readable.  So I think it's reasonable to exit in this case.

EINTER I assume a port from Linux.  EINTER cannot be returned on ThreadX; on Linux it should just retry the read.

commits.commitMessage:
[ATSERVICE] Add atFwdLinker app

In order to implement custom AT commands on ThreadX, forwarding service
is required between the modem and atServer. atFwdLinker app establishes
an interface between atServer and modem using interprocess communication
and ATFWD module provided by Qualcommn.

Resolves: LE-13499 LE-13495
Change-Id: Idde93f215657a62b5f7c4a3df8fa67b8b0348d07
commits.subject: [ATSERVICE] Add atFwdLinker app

comments.message: What is this object used for?  I can tell it's of type AtEvent_t from the declaration without this comment.
Do we need to log when things are OK?
I'd just use this for all error types.  Error strings add up to a surprising amount of space.
This was added by mistake in this patch. Have removed all printfs.
Do we need to log when things are OK?
Yeah, we do not need logging here I already logged before calling qapi_atfwd_reg()
SockFd is client side file descriptor whereas PipeFd is server side file descriptor.
Be careful that this line only works when the data size is smaller than the pipe buffer size (currently 1500). Maybe we should assert that LE_CONFIG_PIPE_BLOCK_SIZE > MAX_RESP_LEN.
If MAX_RESP_LEN > LE_CONFIG_PIPE_BLOCK_SIZE you should read (up to) LE_CONFIG_PIPE_BLOCK_SIZE bytes here.  Which can happen on Linux too, albeit at much higher numbers.

I've added a check to make sure the smaller size buffer is read.
Discussing with Tom, we might want to print a compilation error if pipe block size is less than resp buffer. I've listed it in items to investigate in LE-13646.

As discussed, long term plan should have a while(<fail to register at commands>) { sleep a bit } type of loop.  Can you insert the bug number for the bug that causes QCT to always return success even if registration fails.
Do we need two separate buffers?  Or can we just pass &atCmd[2] to atfwd?

Ran out of time to investigate comments on this file as it requires implementation and testing. Created ticket to address the comments in this file in the next sprint.
https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/LE-13646
No globals please.  Use an accessor function instead.
Why is this used instead of just calling the functions directly?
atQmiLinker uses these. But since in future we might converge with atQmiLinker or atServer. I think we can keep this as is for now. And when we converge, we can make changes accordingly.
Ack.  To be honest, was discussing with Jon and "future convergence" might involve a major re-architecture of atServer.
Shouldn't these be pulled in from some Qualcomm header?  They look like QMI #defines.

There is no Qualcomm file providing these.
I just see other component defining their own e.g in:
qti_bridge.h
atfwd_cli_app.c

Better would be to loop to read as much data as you need.  le_fd_Read() (and read() on Linux) can return any number of bytes from 1 to the amount requested.  Can you add this to your code review comment ticket?
Done. I've added it to LE-13646.

commits.commitMessage:
Add buffer for unsolicited response of AT command

The aim of this new buffer is to avoid a concatenation
of the intermediate response of a given AT command and the
unsolicited response of other AT command.

Resolves: LE-9861
Change-Id: I036a88b130efdd85bec6a3e28aaf8015dff55d53
commits.subject: Add buffer for unsolicited response of AT command

comments.message: Add a proper comment for this variable
Why this is not static anymore?
I don't really see the benefit of this change.

to separate the final response and the unsolicited respons on two different buffer to avoid concatenation of this two responses.
to fix this point of the appropriate ticket:
If an unsolicited response is sent when atLinker is processing intermediate responses of a given AT command, then the unsollicited response is concatenated to the intermediate one. This may lead to a freeze in AT parser. Find a better way to handle the concurrency between unsolicited and intermediate/final responses.

Patch Set 1:

The commit message could explain why we are using static libraries instead of dynamic ones, but basically it's the same old issue of compatibility between what we link against (toolchain) and what's present on the target (rootfs).
If it matches, everything is fine, if it doesn't, the app doesn't start.

By building as static we kill the dependency on the rootfs, so there is no possible mismatch anymore.
Change has been successfully merged by Bertrand Roussel

I didn't get what you mean

>> but I'm not sure why this buffer is needed?
It's there to avoid altering the cmdPtr before being sure that we have something to write to destination buffer.

>> Couldn't we build the command directly in cmdPtr instead?
We can but in case something wrong happens we cannot control it. Using a temporary buffer helps to ensure that a command is received correctly before passing it to the destination buffer

>> Also the memset seems it is used to wipe the whole destination buffer, but I'm not sure why it does that.
It makes sure that the buffer is "empty" before writing a new command in it.

comments.message: Maybe check if callbacks are correctly set by this function before using them?
we can check for null pointers but we cannot be sure that the callbacks are correctly set
Should start with a capital E, no?
this is an inter component function, it should start with a prefix, but I didn't find a good name for now :)
Declaration and initialization can be replaced by SWIQMI_DECLARE_MESSAGE
Yes I am working on it
I think you should use swiQmi_CheckResponse instead
This loop is a bit strange, is it to wait for when QMI is ready?

I find it strange too. Yes that the basic idea, somehow we should wait for qmi to be ready. There a notify callback for the service but not for qmi

This isn't my code, I am using the example given by FW team to enable at cmds forwarding on wp76xx https://gerrit-legato/#/c/16820

I am trying to figure out if there is a better way to do this
I think this should also be passed as an argument if an abortable command needs to be registered, no?
It was decided that we don't want to handle "abortable" commands
Replace by EXIT_FAILURE, same remark for the other exit()
QMI, should be changed in the whole file (sometimes it's "qmi", sometimes "Qmi" in your comments)
If this is a QMI message, should this size be a define provided by QMI headers instead of one defined by you?
This value isn't defined within qmi include files. I am basing my code on the code provided by qmi sources. 512 is the size of the buffer that's all.
As already said, it would be better to use swiQmi_CheckResponse
I don't need it here, checking for the error and logging it is enough

I disagree: swiQmi_CheckResponse logs the result and the error code, which is very important to understand what went wrong.
Your log will only display something like QMI_INTERNAL_ERR, which doesn't help to debug.
swiQmi_CheckRespnose was written to handle qmi_client_send_msg_sync, here we're sending raw messages qmi_client_send_raw_msg_sync which will return the actual error code QMI_INTERNAL_ERR for example
logging the error code is enough
Set RegForPrimaryPort to false in this case?
That one is handled by the error callback. This is weird way to do things but that's how it works

we should read until count == 0
Interruption was taking into account into the previous implementation. It looks it is no more the case
I didn't fix this, I'll leave that for Riadh.

I don't get your comment about the interruption. This is the same code as the previous implementation.

Here we're ignoring the EINTR errno and in case we get interrupted read will return 0 and just cleanup and exit.

about read until count==0, that's what read already does, it'll attempt to read MAX_RESP_LEN and return the max read bytes. If read returns 0 that means that the server closed the other end of the socket hence the client also should cleanup and exit.

Is it a valid response or not, this is handled by sendResponse().
Agreed, we may risk a segfault in this case. It would be better to treat EINTR like all errors, just cleanup and exit. We should also send a ERROR response to the user

commits.commitMessage:
Modifying the atQmiLinker to initialize the ATCOP service for WP76XX.

Issue:
atQmiLinker application was not working on WP76xx and hence could not
test if the AT+WDS commands that are forwarded would be handled
by legato.
atQmiLinker is not working since the qmi intialization fails. This is
because the app uses 'qmi_init' to initialize the qmi and which ends up
calling 'linux_qmi_qmux_if_client_init' which errors out giving a
message 'qmi_client <client ID> QMUXD disabled' as a flag
'FEATURE_QMUXD_DISABLED' has been defined to force this in WP76XX.

Solution:
Used 'qmi_client_init_instance' to initialize the atcop service.
Also made changes to send messages back to modem as the client handle
is not exposed on calling 'qmi_client_init_instance' instead a pointer
to a structure containing the handle is received.
The changes depend on changes in QTI9X07-415

Resolves: QTI9X07-415
Change-Id: I6d9c44f6a91c3f8d0243c4f8fd98bd00bc2b0879
commits.subject: Modifying the atQmiLinker to initialize the ATCOP service for WP76XX.

comments.message:
Actually this doesn't work either.  Then you'll just end up resending the starting bytes each time.  I think you need a separate variable for the start of unsent data, which you update every time you update the size.  Or track the original size and change your write() function to:

    write(AtQmiLinker.sockFd, AtQmiLinker.cmd+(totalSize-size), size);

this is Ok actually.
this is the case where count = -1 and errno = EINTR which means that no data has been sent which is Ok for us and we need to resend the whole buffer.

But you're always setting count back to 0, not just if count=-1 && errno=EINTR.

Imagine this situation:

Initially:
    AtQmiLinker.cmd = "\r\nsometextgoeshere\r\n"
    size = 20

Now 6 bytes are sent by write.  Now you have
    count = 6
    size = 14

Originally you would call write(sockFd, "textgoeshere\r\n", 14).  After your change you will call write(sockFd, "\r\nsometextogeshere\r\n", 14), causing the first part of your message to be sent twice, and the last 6 bytes to be not sent at all.

But even in the original code, if the second write only sends a few bytes (say another 6), when you repeat the write you will do write(sockFd, "textgoeshere\r\n", 8); again resending the first part of the buffer, and cutting more off of the end.

This is why I think we need a le_fd_Write() to handle all these cases.

Anyway I would suggest either:

1) Handle any number of retries correctly, or
2) Treat any partial write as a fail and just exit, without trying to retry at all (only retry on count == -1 && errno == EINTR).

As you say such a short message should generally not fail.

I don't agree with you on le_fd_Write(). I think that every write is unique and depends on the way we're going to use it. With a le_fd_Write() we'll end up with a lot of dead code for simple writes, like in this case.

My proposed le_fd_Write() would be almost identical to your fdWrite().  Sure, there's a lot of fancy things you can do with write(), but 99.95% of cases are writing an entire buffer, ignoring interruptions from signals.  But there's still a lot of subtlety & boilerplate code in that simple case.
it's more of a double check but yes we can just verify size
Personally I'd move this out into the parent.

commits.commitMessage:
Add QCT ATCOP client

Registers as a client to the atcop service to forward received
AT commands.
Registers as a client to the atServer to parse AT commands.
Builds forwarded AT commands and transfers them to the atServer
to be parsed.
Sends the received responses to the atcop service.

Note:
  faultAction is set to ignore as qmi doesn't release atcop
  service clients properly.
  To be able to restart this app we need to restart all atcop
  service clients.

Resolves: LE-6518
Change-Id: Idfe50c8a9399c5be6bbf7cb551f3e1fb6439869e
commits.subject: Add QCT ATCOP client

comments.message:
I would like to see if we can avoid to call that Makefile before we run releaselegato but it is not an easy task.

I guess we could have some kind of hook in the legato/Makefile that goes through all legato/apps/proprietary/*/Makefile and runs 'make <target>' before calling 'releaselegato'.

That's quite simple, but wonder if we could have an option in mksys that just generates a binary package for all apps in the system by default, that way we really don't have to maintain that integration at all and that might benefit some customers. Another possibility would be to have an option in the .adef that says 'hey while you're at it generate a binary package for this app' which would be set only for proprietary apps.

This is a manual build Makefile, for testing.
We can call it from the Legato's main Makefile but I think that it would be better to have a "sdef / sinc" file that "builds all the apps / fetches the binaries" and in the target sdef file we add the binaries.

If I understand the dependency in on qmi_atcop_srvc.h.
Could we do some test on the presence of LEGATO_PROPRIETARY_QCT_DIR/inc/framework/qmi_atcop_srvc.h.
If it is there, we can build the app, and if not it is not supported.

What do you think?
Not just qmi_atcop_srvc.h, the modem must support the forwarding of at cmds. For now only wp85 supports it.

We need to decouple this app as much as we can from wp85.
Could you use LEGATO_PROPRIETARY_QCT_DIR here instead?

command

The coding standards are pretty clear in term of which word can be abbreviated or not: http://legato.io/legato-docs/latest/ccodingStdsAbbr.html

It also says:
Note
  Propose additions if you feel something's missing.

cmd is a well known abbreviation of command.
In which case I think you should also submit a patch against the coding standard at the same time.

QMI

For pthread_cond_t looks like there is no such abstraction for it in liblegato :/
Maybe we should add one, that's worth creating a ticket for it to investigate.

rcv is also a well known abbreviation of receive
why not integer ?

Because boolean is limited to 2 states so it is clear that it's either one or the other.
Here it is not clear:
-x = ?
0 = a command has not been received?
1 = a command has been received
x = ? forbidden values?
Right ... so it's a boolean basically ...
(I see that is has been fixed in latest patch).

registered

Half of your comments have typos ://
le_signal doesn't support sigsets and I need to wait for all possible signals to be able to cleanup before exiting
Or you could have a handler to handle that you provide to le_signal?

According to le_signal.api le_sig_SetEventHandler() supports only one signal at a time + each signal can only have a single event handler per thread +  "SIGFPE, SIGILL, SIGSEGV, SIGBUS, SIGABRT, SIGIOT, SIGTRAP, SIGEMT, SIGSYS" are not supported.

This is worth splitting into multiple functions.
The current one is hardly readable.
Using signals as an inter-thread communication mechanism is fraught with peril.  Can this be done with an event instead?

agreed.
This should be handled differently
I wonder if this should go in /var/lib or /var/run instead?  /tmp is only intended for temporary files.
Most places on the target are read-only (especially with the 'read-only' mode enabled), except /tmp

Is there a RFS standard somewhere?  /var is on a tempfs on WP85, which is what I was basing this on.

I expect at least parts of /var to be writable on all platforms as many standard Linux programs don't work otherwise.
Oh right /var is also a tmpfs, so that would be a more suitable place.

@Keith the atBinder socket is temporary and is created by the atBinder process each time it starts. I agree with you on that(/var). Usually on Linux systems we put this kind of files in "/var/run/process.pid/file". I guess that it would be better to create an issue tracker to fix this in atBinder code.

@Bertrand /var is a tmpfs just like /tmp and is mounted rw.
Do you need to pass the size of this buffer to avoid buffer overflows?

snprintf is there to avoid buffer overflows, the only risk is that the string will be truncated to CMD_SIZE.
I don't think that we will exceed 127 bytes but what we can also do to be sure:
#define CMD_SIZE  (QMI_ATCOP_AT_CMD_NAME_MAX_LEN + (QMI_ATCOP_MAX_TOKEN_SIZE * QMI_ATCOP_MAX_TOKENS))

snprintf only helps if you know the size of the buffer, and you're not passing the buffer size into this function, so you need to assume the size of the buffer passed in.  Since this is a static function this is kind-of OK as you always control the buffer being passed in, but I think it's still good practice to pass in the buffer size whenever you pass in an output buffer.

Up to you though.
Why not strncpy(cmdPtr, <size of cmdPtr>, cmd)?  Or better yet, just build up the command in cmdPtr and avoid the copy altogether.

memcpy to copy the whole buffer.
It's safer to not write to the output buffer until everything goes Ok
Maybe at least log an invalid/abort indication has been received?
Since you've just done a memset, won't strlen(buf) be 0 at this point?
What about errno == EINTER (especially if you're using SIGABRT for inter-thread communication)?  What about partial writes?

agreed.
But I don't think that waiting for the write to finish would be useful, atBinder will catch that the client has disconnected and will restart atServer.

It's not about waiting for the write to finish.  write() can write less than the amount of data passed in if (for example) the socket buffer is full.  The remaining data is not queued, it's just dropped.

if write is interrupted then:
- no data has been written, it fails with -1 and sets errno to EINTR
- few bytes has been written then it returns the number of bytes it wrote before interruption.

in both cases we don't care, if we get here this means that we just need to cleanup and exit.

In case of EINTR it might be best to retry until we finish the write.
Seems fragile to fail because we got an EINTR :/

Why do you want to fail on partial write instead of just finishing the rest of the write?  And at the moment it *doesn't* cleanup an exit on partial write -- it only cleans up and exits if *no* data was written.

@Bertrand: let's say we finish the write, this means that atServer will detect that a command is issued and tries to process it, meanwhile atQmiLinker has exited which will be detected by the atServer and simply the processing will be dropped, + this isn't like some super high sensitive data that needs to be sent to the sever, it's just a forwarded AT command.

@Keith: the cleanup is done by the CleanupHandler.
I think you missed my point -- partial writes are treated as successes (i.e. try to write 10 bytes but only write 5).  IMO these should either be errors, or preferably write the remaining 5 bytes.
This raises SIGABRT in the *current* thread, not the main thread.

agreed
It has to be pthread_kill(main_thread_id, SIGABRT).
I used raise in development process just to check that we never get there as the socket is supposed to be available
Complete the line up to 100 chars

what is the meaning of "sMutex" ? why "s" ?
I guess "qMutex" means "qmiMutex". I think complete words improves the readability

s for server

yes why not
This could be added into BuildAtCommand(), as the AT command is built into the other function

maybe better to check 
OK
 and 
ERROR
 in order to not catch intermediate answer like this:
+TOTO: OK


OK

This case doesn't exist with +WDS* commands, but...
I'vs never seen this kind of intermediate responses but sure why not
Why do we need this mutex here ?
Maybe call LE_FATAL instead?  That way you can log an error message as well.
LE_FATAL exits immediately which can be an issue, we need to do the cleanup before exiting especially qmi stuff
Oh, I see what's going on now.  I think it's somewhat confusing to use signal numbers here when this doesn't go through signal handlers at all.  Not a big deal though.
instead of defining a new variable to describe that we're aborting I used SIGABRT which is just an integer so no big deal
A more descriptive name like "CleanupEvent" would be nice.  Same below.
Why not just call the cleanup function directly from here instead of raising another event?
because I cannot pass data to SigHandler which means that I'll have to use global variables
I need to have access to atQmiLinker contextPtr to de register qmi stuff

atQmiLinker is almost a global (really file-scope) variable anyway since it's static, so I'm not sure making it a file-scope variable is a bad thing.  But I can see your point.

My concern was that there will be a race condition where you have:

SIGTERM caught (here) ~> <some code that assumes not shutting down> ~> CleanupHandler called.  

But since this does nothing but trigger the cleanup handler it looks fine.

for wp76xx compatibility, we need to add "-lqmi_client_qmux".
Otherwise this does not link.
If -1 == count && EINTR == errno this will incorrectly add one to the size, leading to a 1-byte overflow on reading the buffer.
